# ANSIBLE GENERAL NOTES

## 💡 CONCEPTS

| Term | Definition |
|------|------------|
| **Automation** | The use of machines or technology to perform tasks without much human intervention |
| **BPA** | Business Process Automation |
| **IaC** | Infrastructure as Code |
| **Collection** | A packaging format for bundling and distributing Ansible content, including plugins, roles, modules, and more |
| **Control Nodes** | Any host with Ansible installed. Ansible control nodes are primarily used to run tasks on managed hosts |
| **Managed Hosts** | Hosts (Servers) that you manage using Ansible |
| **Inventory** | A list of managed nodes |
| **Hostfile** | An inventory file is often known as a hostfile. In it, you can specify your inventory using IPs or hostnames and can organize them into groups |
| **Tasks** | Actions that Ansible performs on a managed host. You can perform a single task using ad-hoc commands |
| **Ansible Playbooks** | Lists of repeatable tasks (scripts) written in YAML Ain't Markup Language (YAML), which makes them easy to read, write, and share |
| **Module** | Small piece of code. Modules are the units of work that Ansible ships out to remote machines |
| **Plug-ins** | Code that you can add to Ansible to extend it and adapt it to new uses and platforms. Complementos o código complementario que se puede agregar y extiende las capacidades de Ansible |
| **Red Hat Ansible Tower** | Automation Controller |
| **Roles** | Units of organization in Ansible |
| **PyPI** | Python Package Index |
| **Ad Hoc Command** | A way of executing a single Ansible task quickly, one that you do not need to save to run again later. They are simple, online operations that can be run without writing a playbook |
| **Pattern** | An Ansible pattern can refer to a single host, an IP address, an inventory group, a set of groups, or all hosts in your inventory |
| **Task** | The application of a module to perform a specific unit of work |
| **Play** | A sequence of tasks to be applied, in order, to one or more hosts selected from your inventory |
| **Playbook** | A text file containing a list of one or more plays to run in a specific order |
| **Block** | Blocks create logical groups of tasks. Blocks also offer ways to handle task errors, similar to exception handling in many programming languages |
| **Library** | Ansible refers to the collection of available modules as a library |

